# What is Firewall management::::::::::::::::

Firewall management is the process of configuring and maintaining a firewall to control incoming and outgoing network traffic based on security rules.

# what is firewall ::::::::::::::::::::::

A firewall is a system that:

ðŸ›‘ Blocks or allows traffic based on predefined rules.
ðŸ” Inspects packets and decides whether to forward, drop, or reject them.
ðŸšª Protects ports, protocols, and services from unauthorized access.

# Linux Firewall Tools:::::::::::::

| Tool          | Description                                                         |
| ------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **iptables**  | Legacy, low-level tool to define firewall rules                     |
| **nftables**  | Modern replacement for iptables (since kernel 3.13)                 |
| **firewalld** | High-level service using `iptables/nftables` (dynamic, easy-to-use) |
| **ufw**       | Simplified front-end for `iptables` (mainly on Ubuntu)              |

# Common Linux Firewall Tools in Action::::::::::::::

1. ðŸ§± firewalld
Start/Stop/Enable:

sudo systemctl start firewalld
sudo systemctl enable firewalld
sudo systemctl status firewalld

Check default zone:
firewall-cmd --get-default-zone

Allow a service (e.g. HTTP):
firewall-cmd --add-service=http --permanent
firewall-cmd --reload

Block a port:
firewall-cmd --remove-port=8080/tcp --permanent
firewall-cmd --reload

List all rules:
firewall-cmd --list-all

2. ðŸ”— iptables (low-level)
Allow SSH:
sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

Block IP:
sudo iptables -A INPUT -s 192.168.1.100 -j DROP

Save rules:
sudo iptables-save > /etc/iptables/rules.v4

3. ðŸš¦ UFW (Uncomplicated Firewall â€“ Ubuntu)
Enable firewall:
sudo ufw enable

Allow ports:
sudo ufw allow 22
sudo ufw LLOW 80/tcp

Deny traffic:
sudo ufw deny 23

Check status:
sudo ufw status

